Below are production-ready steps to regenerate the kube-apiserver serving certificate so it’s valid when clients connect using the public IP (example `103.154.75.23:6443`) — i.e., it fixes the exact error: “cert is valid for private IPs, not public IP”.

These steps assume:

* single control-plane (`10.48.243.135`)
* kubeadm-managed cluster (you have `kubeadm-config` ConfigMap)
* clients will access directly via public IP (no domain)

---

 0) Before you start (safety)

Run on the master:


sudo -i
mkdir -p /root/cert-backup-$(date +%F)
cp -a /etc/kubernetes/pki/apiserver.{crt,key} /root/cert-backup-$(date +%F)/
cp -a /etc/kubernetes/admin.conf /root/cert-backup-$(date +%F)/


---

 1) Confirm current SANs (you’ll see public IP missing)


openssl x509 -in /etc/kubernetes/pki/apiserver.crt -noout -text | grep -A1 "Subject Alternative Name"


---

 2) Remove/move existing apiserver cert/key (kubeadm won’t overwrite)

> kubeadm will skip generation if files already exist. ([man.archlinux.org][1])


mv /etc/kubernetes/pki/apiserver.crt /root/cert-backup-$(date +%F)/apiserver.crt.old
mv /etc/kubernetes/pki/apiserver.key /root/cert-backup-$(date +%F)/apiserver.key.old


---

 3) Generate new apiserver cert with public IP in SAN

Use the kubeadm phase command and add the public IP as an extra SAN:


kubeadm init phase certs apiserver --apiserver-cert-extra-sans 103.154.75.23


This flag explicitly adds SAN entries and avoids config parsing issues. ([mankier.com][2])

> If you also want it to work with a domain later, you can add it too:
> `--apiserver-cert-extra-sans k8s-api.akrys.ai`
> (Not required for “IP-only” access.)

---

 4) Restart kube-apiserver (static pod) to pick up the new cert

kube-apiserver is a static pod, so touching its manifest forces a restart:


touch /etc/kubernetes/manifests/kube-apiserver.yaml


Then watch it come back:


crictl ps | grep kube-apiserver || true
kubectl -n kube-system get pods | grep kube-apiserver || true


(Alternative is stopping/removing the apiserver pod via `crictl`; touching the manifest is the cleanest.)

---

 5) Verify new SAN contains the public IP


openssl x509 -in /etc/kubernetes/pki/apiserver.crt -noout -text | grep -A1 "Subject Alternative Name"


You should now see:

* `IP Address:103.154.75.23`
* plus your existing internal SANs

---

 6) Client-side kubeconfig change (required)

Clients must point to the public IP:

yaml
server: https://103.154.75.23:6443


They should keep the existing `certificate-authority-data` (cluster CA) — because the apiserver cert is still signed by the Kubernetes CA.

---

 7) (Recommended) Store this SAN config for future upgrades

Kubernetes recommends keeping kubeadm config updated for future operations. ([Kubernetes][3])

Create a kubeadm config file with SANs and upload it:


kubectl -n kube-system get configmap kubeadm-config -o jsonpath='{.data.ClusterConfiguration}' > /root/kubeadm-cluster.yaml


Edit `/root/kubeadm-cluster.yaml` and add:

yaml
apiServer:
  certSANs:
  - "103.154.75.23"


Then upload:


kubeadm init phase upload-config kubeadm --config /root/kubeadm-cluster.yaml


> Note: If your kubeadm build complains about `certSANs` in v1beta4, keep the file as internal documentation and rely on the `--apiserver-cert-extra-sans` approach for regeneration.

---

 8) Remove HAProxy / load balancer path (since IP-only direct access)

Once you confirm `kubectl` works via public IP:

* Remove NAT mapping to HAProxy port (9443) and point public `6443 → private 6443`
* Stop/disable HAProxy on master if not needed:


systemctl stop haproxy
systemctl disable haproxy


